00:33:14,703 --> 00:33:17,761
My, er, fiancee's expecting me.

536
00:33:18,629 --> 00:33:19,708
Yeah.

537
00:33:19,742 --> 00:33:21,932
My brother will have to drive you into town

538
00:33:21,966 --> 00:33:24,538
because Susan smashed up my dad's car.

539
00:33:25,581 --> 00:33:26,624
Fine.

540
00:33:27,458 --> 00:33:28,535
See you in the morning.

541
00:33:28,535 --> 00:33:30,865
Oh, well. Thanks again, Fred.

542
00:33:34,061 --> 00:33:35,487
(CREAKING)

543
00:33:38,824 --> 00:33:39,971
(SIGHS)

544
00:33:40,040 --> 00:33:42,334
-(KNOCKING) -FRED: Richard?

545
00:33:45,218 --> 00:33:46,991
(CREAKING)

546
00:33:47,512 --> 00:33:48,938
Just one more thing.

547
00:33:50,849 --> 00:33:51,892
Lock the door.

548
00:33:57,037 --> 00:34:00,303
(CREAKING)

549
00:34:44,653 --> 00:34:46,008
(CLUCKING)

550
00:34:52,404 --> 00:34:54,142
(GUNSHOT)

551
00:35:07,107 --> 00:35:08,358
Oh, shit.

552
00:35:08,671 --> 00:35:09,886
What?

553
00:35:12,772 --> 00:35:16,421
I have some good news and some bad news.

554
00:35:16,456 --> 00:35:19,236
The bad news is that Susan took Dennis car out this morning

555
00:35:19,271 --> 00:35:21,043
and she hasn't returned.

556
00:35:21,113 --> 00:35:23,025
Great. What's the good news?

557
00:35:23,025 --> 00:35:24,728
My sister cut and dyed your hair.

558
00:35:32,027 --> 00:35:33,070
This,

559
00:35:33,660 --> 00:35:35,468
this is crazy!

560
00:35:35,503 --> 00:35:37,554
Why would she do this? It's...

561
00:35:38,214 --> 00:35:40,265
it's only one side.

562
00:35:40,299 --> 00:35:42,663
I'm guessing you were probably sleeping on the other.

563
00:35:42,697 --> 00:35:44,679
This is good news?

564
00:35:44,679 --> 00:35:45,826
Yes, it is good news.

565
00:35:45,860 --> 00:35:46,973
It doesn't look

566
00:35:47,945 --> 00:35:48,988
half bad.

567
00:35:49,718 --> 00:35:51,735
You think this is funny?

568
00:35:51,803 --> 00:35:54,097
Who, in their right mind,

569
00:35:54,133 --> 00:36:00,389
comes into someone's room in the middle of the night and cuts their hair?

570
00:36:00,423 --> 00:36:01,675
My sister Celia.

571
00:36:03,204 --> 00:36:05,533
You see, she dreams of being a hair stylist

572
00:36:05,567 --> 00:36:08,591
and when she sleep walks, she cuts hair.

573
00:36:08,626 --> 00:36:10,572
Doesn't even remember doing it.

574
00:36:10,642 --> 00:36:12,345
I told you to lock the door.

575
00:36:12,345 --> 00:36:13,631
Pinch me.

576
00:36:14,430 --> 00:36:16,377
-What? -Just pinch me.

577
00:36:16,411 --> 00:36:17,802
Maybe I'm dreaming.

578
00:36:20,096 --> 00:36:21,278
Ow.

579
00:36:21,348 --> 00:36:22,599
Are you dreaming?

580
00:36:22,633 --> 00:36:23,676
No.

581
00:36:23,710 --> 00:36:25,587
(FOOTSTEPS)

582
00:36:25,623 --> 00:36:27,881
Dad, you remember Richard?

583
00:36:27,917 --> 00:36:29,828
(SHOUTS)

584
00:36:31,809 --> 00:36:32,956
(DOOR BANGS CLOSE)

585
00:36:36,119 --> 00:36:37,161
Hates your hair.

586
00:36:38,448 --> 00:36:40,081
(CUCKOO CLOCK CHIMING)

587
00:36:41,576 --> 00:36:43,904
Oh, I like your new dippity-do.

588
00:36:46,824 --> 00:36:49,118
-Hey, mom, do I smell bacon? -(CHIRPING)

589
00:36:49,152 --> 00:36:52,525
Freddie, you know Jimmy doesn't like the word "bacon".

590
00:36:52,559 --> 00:36:56,730
Oh, now you've made me say ba... B-A-C-O-N.

591
00:36:58,224 --> 00:37:00,205
I've found the perfect Christmas tree.

592
00:37:00,205 --> 00:37:02,082
It just needs a little trimming.

593
00:37:02,082 --> 00:37:06,288
Speaking of trims, Richard, Celia, Celia, Richard.

594
00:37:06,323 --> 00:37:08,304
Oh, I did that to your hair.

595
00:37:08,374 --> 00:37:09,625
I'm very sorry.

596
00:37:09,659 --> 00:37:11,085
(RUNNING FOOTSTEPS)

597
00:37:12,857 --> 00:37:14,247
Go get 'em, dad!

598
00:37:17,306 --> 00:37:20,746
Oh, no. Thank you. I never eat breakfast.

599
00:37:20,782 --> 00:37:22,902
(GUNSHOT)

600
00:37:22,936 --> 00:37:25,370
But, I am feeling a bit peckish.

601
00:37:25,370 --> 00:37:29,679
I really, really need to use your phone.

602
00:37:29,749 --> 00:37:31,243
There's one down the hall in the den.

603
00:37:33,780 --> 00:37:35,414
(GUNSHOT)

604
00:37:49,178 --> 00:37:51,506
Thanks for blowing it, Celia.

605
00:37:52,098 --> 00:37:53,349
What did I do?

606
00:37:53,383 --> 00:37:55,191
The guy's a magician.

607
00:37:55,191 --> 00:37:56,720
A real magician?

608
00:37:56,755 --> 00:37:58,945
Yeah. Saw him at the club last night.

609
00:38:10,067 --> 00:38:11,109
(DIAL TONE)

610
00:38:16,358 --> 00:38:17,610
(LINE RINGS)

611
00:38:17,644 --> 00:38:18,930
SARA: Hello.

612
00:38:18,965 --> 00:38:19,904
Sara?

613
00:38:19,904 --> 00:38:21,259
Richard, where are you?

614
00:38:21,294 --> 00:38:23,379
Outside of this town called Slygo.

615
00:38:23,413 --> 00:38:24,839
I booked it.

616
00:38:24,873 --> 00:38:27,515
-What? -The hall I was talking about.

617
00:38:27,550 --> 00:38:30,608
Good. I'm in a bit of a situation here.

618
00:38:31,269 --> 00:38:32,902
Oh, you found the phone.

619
00:38:34,293 --> 00:38:35,717
Who's there with you?

620
00:38:36,551 --> 00:38:38,672
What? No one.

621
00:38:38,707 --> 00:38:41,244
But, I, I heard a woman's voice, Richard.

622
00:38:41,279 --> 00:38:43,712
Just me here. I'm all alone. No one else but, me.

623
00:38:43,746 --> 00:38:44,963
(WHISPERS) This is a private call.

624
00:38:45,346 --> 00:38:46,493
Oh.

625
00:38:51,324 --> 00:38:53,026
What do you think?

626
00:38:53,026 --> 00:38:55,460
Food stations or, a fixed meal?

627
00:38:55,494 --> 00:38:57,962
I'm all for it. Look, I'm at this house.

628
00:38:58,797 --> 00:38:59,839
Sara?

629
00:39:00,638 --> 00:39:02,306
Sara? Hello?

630
00:39:02,932 --> 00:39:03,975
Hello?

631
00:39:04,462 --> 00:39:05,504
Richard?

632
00:39:05,817 --> 00:39:07,034
Hello?

633
00:39:07,590 --> 00:39:09,224
Hello!

634
00:39:09,224 --> 00:39:10,996
Great, the phone just went dead.

635
00:39:11,031 --> 00:39:13,151
Hmm, does that when it storms.

636
00:39:18,434 --> 00:39:19,755
You know, my parents designed this room

637
00:39:19,789 --> 00:39:22,362
after they went to Vegas on their second honeymoon.

638
00:39:22,431 --> 00:39:24,760
Sometimes pictures just aren't enough.

639
00:39:28,514 --> 00:39:29,834
Who's Sara?

640
00:39:30,286 --> 00:39:31,468
My fiancee.

641
00:39:31,502 --> 00:39:32,962
Why did you lie to her?

642
00:39:32,997 --> 00:39:34,387
I didn't lie.

643
00:39:34,422 --> 00:39:37,377
What, you mean about me being alone in the room?

644
00:39:38,837 --> 00:39:40,192
She gets upset.

645
00:39:40,227 --> 00:39:43,076
I dunno, it was just, it was more like a white lie, you know.

646
00:39:43,112 --> 00:39:44,502
Oh, a white lie.

647
00:39:44,502 --> 00:39:45,892
What colour's truth?

648
00:39:46,587 --> 00:39:48,360
-"Truth?" -Yeah.

649
00:39:49,055 --> 00:39:50,237
I don't know.

650
00:39:50,271 --> 00:39:52,600
I think truth is a rainbow.

651
00:39:52,669 --> 00:39:54,720
-Really? -Yes.

652
00:39:54,720 --> 00:39:58,544
You know, they say when you see someone's true colours, you're really seeing them.

653
00:39:58,578 --> 00:40:01,602
And to see someone's true colours, means to see the truth.

654
00:40:02,262 --> 00:40:04,035
So truth must be many colours.

655
00:40:05,113 --> 00:40:06,503
Don't you think?

656
00:40:06,503 --> 00:40:08,762
I never thought about it.

657
00:40:08,831 --> 00:40:10,917
You were probably too busy with work.

658
00:40:11,647 --> 00:40:13,142
My father worked.

659
00:40:13,211 --> 00:40:16,652
It was his job to put the snow in these snow bubbles.

660
00:40:16,687 --> 00:40:19,120
And then he got replaced by a robot.

661
00:40:19,154 --> 00:40:22,908
I guess no one's job's safe these days.

662
00:40:22,943 --> 00:40:24,403
That's the truth.

663
00:40:25,202 --> 00:40:27,391
This one is my favourite.

664
00:40:37,471 --> 00:40:39,244
I could watch these for days.

665
00:40:40,774 --> 00:40:42,963
They're like little windows into other worlds.

666
00:40:45,083 --> 00:40:47,064
Fred said you're a magician.

667
00:40:47,690 --> 00:40:50,401
Yeah. Well, used to be.

668
00:40:50,435 --> 00:40:53,981
Oh. How do you stop being magic?

669
00:40:54,016 --> 00:40:55,962
You ask a lot of questions.

670
00:40:56,032 --> 00:40:58,047
How else do you get a lot of answers?

671
00:40:59,194 --> 00:41:00,862
Good point.

672
00:41:00,862 --> 00:41:03,643
I bet you started as a kid, right?

673
00:41:03,678 --> 00:41:05,833
Yeah, when I was around ten or, so.

674
00:41:07,223 --> 00:41:09,691
That's what's great about being a kid.

675
00:41:09,725 --> 00:41:11,498
You can dream about becoming whatever you want

676
00:41:11,498 --> 00:41:13,896
and no one can tell you you can't 'cause you believe.

677
00:41:13,932 --> 00:41:18,311
Doctor, astronaut, an Indian chief.

678
00:41:18,346 --> 00:41:20,882
I mean think about, if no one ever grew up,

679
00:41:20,918 --> 00:41:23,525
there'd be so many Indian chiefs.

680
00:41:23,559 --> 00:41:27,487
Guess I, er, experienced your dream last night.

681
00:41:27,487 --> 00:41:28,530
DAD: Celia!

682
00:41:29,364 --> 00:41:30,615
Coming!

683
00:41:32,422 --> 00:41:34,682
Can you do a magic show for my father?

684
00:41:34,716 --> 00:41:36,489
I really can't stay.

685
00:41:36,489 --> 00:41:37,601
Teach me, then.

686
00:41:45,247 --> 00:41:48,931
-(MUMBLES) -(CHUCKLES)

687
00:41:58,837 --> 00:42:00,888
(WIND HOWLING)

688
00:42:08,465 --> 00:42:09,925
(LINE RINGS)

689
00:42:09,960 --> 00:42:11,107
What?

690
00:42:11,141 --> 00:42:12,741
OPERATOR: Collect call from a Mr Richard Wilson.

691
00:42:12,775 --> 00:42:14,269
Will you accept the charge?

692
00:42:14,305 --> 00:42:15,625
Richard?

693
00:42:15,625 --> 00:42:17,710
Ah, yes! Er, George.

694
00:42:17,780 --> 00:42:20,108
Er, Mr. Billings, sir.

695
00:42:20,144 --> 00:42:21,916
-(GUNSHOT) -Where the hell are you?

696
00:42:21,985 --> 00:42:26,226
Richard, the, the Yamashitsu executives are arriving here tonight.

697
00:42:26,260 --> 00:42:29,041
I'll be there soon. It's just, uh...

698
00:42:29,945 --> 00:42:31,197
(GUNSHOT)

699
00:42:31,197 --> 00:42:34,706
(EXCLAIMING)

700
00:42:34,706 --> 00:42:36,966
Help...

701
00:42:37,000 --> 00:42:38,113
Richard?

702
00:42:38,113 --> 00:42:39,190
...me.

703
00:42:39,225 --> 00:42:40,303
Richard?

704
00:42:43,396 --> 00:42:45,029
Oh, God, he's gone again.

705
00:42:55,943 --> 00:42:57,750
You didn't tell him anything, did you?

706
00:42:58,724 --> 00:43:00,218
I told him about himself.

707
00:43:00,878 --> 00:43:01,921
Oh.

708
00:43:03,068 --> 00:43:05,153
Did you mention the curse?

709
00:43:05,223 --> 00:43:07,204
He's going to teach me magic.

710
00:43:07,239 --> 00:43:08,490
What? You?

711
00:43:08,526 --> 00:43:09,846
(KETTLE HISSING)

712
00:43:09,881 --> 00:43:12,452
'Cause Dad will never believe you having magical powers.

713
00:43:12,488 --> 00:43:15,199
I'm the one who has to go to Paris, Fred.

714
00:43:15,268 --> 00:43:18,014
Celia, we all want this curse to end.

715
00:43:30,665 --> 00:43:32,508
Are you a little warmer now?

716
00:43:32,542 --> 00:43:33,932
Yeah, thanks.

717
00:43:33,968 --> 00:43:35,183
Good.

718
00:43:40,293 --> 00:43:42,101
Er, Dennis.

719
00:43:42,135 --> 00:43:45,159
Listen, could you run me back to town?

720
00:43:45,193 --> 00:43:46,584
Yeah, you're gonna have to run.

721
00:43:46,619 --> 00:43:49,851
Susan just wrapped my car around a stinking lamppost.

722
00:43:51,694 --> 00:43:53,431
My gifts, my bags!

723
00:43:54,543 --> 00:43:58,263
God damn curse! I was almost out of here!

724
00:43:58,332 --> 00:43:59,827
-What happened? -I wiped out.

725
00:43:59,861 --> 00:44:02,711
What the hell do you think happened, chucklebutt?

726
00:44:02,711 --> 00:44:04,762
Who invited the Selsun blue guy?

727
00:44:11,227 --> 00:44:12,930
Oh my God, my bags.

728
00:44:14,738 --> 00:44:17,274
Hey, hey. Rachini Garabini.

729
00:44:17,309 --> 00:44:19,013
We've gotta stop meeting like this.

730
00:44:19,013 --> 00:44:21,375
Where are my presents?

731
00:44:21,375 --> 00:44:23,565
Sorry, I didn't get you anything this year.

732
00:44:27,667 --> 00:44:28,710
RICHARD: Wait!

733
00:44:34,201 --> 00:44:37,712
Billy I need a ride.

734
00:44:37,712 --> 00:44:39,102
Thousand bucks.

735
00:44:40,597 --> 00:44:41,917
Or, a trick.

736
00:44:42,995 --> 00:44:45,289
(BOTH GRUNTING)

737
00:44:48,973 --> 00:44:50,571
(SCREAMS)

738
00:44:51,197 --> 00:44:52,240
Ow.

739
00:44:52,275 --> 00:44:54,082
That's a hell of a fall, Richard.

740
00:44:54,152 --> 00:44:55,438
Wow.

741
00:44:56,272 --> 00:44:58,044
How are you? Are you okay?

742
00:44:58,740 --> 00:45:02,389
I am in a circle of hell...

743
00:45:02,424 --> 00:45:04,961
(SHOUTS) that Dante never even dreamed of.

744
00:45:06,525 --> 00:45:07,672
Be that as it may,

745
00:45:07,707 --> 00:45:10,279
Uh, my aunt and uncle are coming over for dinner.

746
00:45:10,314 --> 00:45:12,051
-Yes. -They have a car.

747
00:45:12,087 --> 00:45:13,998
Yes, they have a car.

748
00:45:14,068 --> 00:45:15,770
Let's go inside and take care of you.

749
00:45:15,805 --> 00:45:18,169
-Warm clothes? Warm clothes? -Get you warm.

750
00:45:18,239 --> 00:45:19,524
FRED: No, it looks good.

751
00:45:19,559 --> 00:45:21,401
Apparently it belonged to Liberace.

752
00:45:21,436 --> 00:45:24,772
Besides, it's either that or you'll have to wear Dennis clothes.

753
00:45:25,189 --> 00:45:26,649
Fine, fine.

754
00:45:26,685 --> 00:45:29,291
So, how long will it take for my suit to dry?

755
00:45:29,291 --> 00:45:33,392
Would a suit be "delicate", "permanent press" or "normal dry"?

756
00:45:33,983 --> 00:45:35,512
Normal, I guess.

757
00:45:37,007 --> 00:45:38,780
So as soon as your uncle gets here,

758
00:45:38,814 --> 00:45:41,213
-you can give me a ride straight into town, right? -(DRYER BEEPING)

759
00:45:41,282 --> 00:45:44,062
I have a confession to make.

760
00:45:44,098 --> 00:45:47,260
I arranged with the MC that you would lose the contest.

761
00:45:47,295 --> 00:45:49,624
After you knew I needed the money?

762
00:45:49,624 --> 00:45:52,195
Well, I need your help to lift the curse.

763
00:45:53,030 --> 00:45:54,629
"Curse?"

764
00:45:54,664 --> 00:45:55,985
The curse of the...

765
00:45:57,618 --> 00:45:58,487
wild turkey.

766
00:45:58,556 --> 00:46:00,920
"The curse of the wild turkey?"

767
00:46:00,954 --> 00:46:04,743
As long as the turkey is around our house, we, we can't leave.

768
00:46:04,778 --> 00:46:07,593
In fact, we have to be back by midnight.

769
00:46:08,462 --> 00:46:10,443
My nana put this curse on my dad.

770
00:46:10,443 --> 00:46:11,973
They didn't get along.

771
00:46:13,015 --> 00:46:15,101
But, my dad believes in magic.

772
00:46:15,101 --> 00:46:16,422
Real magic.

773
00:46:16,456 --> 00:46:19,167
And I thought you could convince him that you have powers,

774
00:46:19,202 --> 00:46:21,948
then he'd believe that you can lift the curse.

775
00:46:22,017 --> 00:46:23,338
You're serious?

776
00:46:23,372 --> 00:46:25,389
I was thinking a magic show.

777
00:46:25,423 --> 00:46:27,822
Something small, just to get him interested,

778
00:46:27,892 --> 00:46:30,984
and then tell him that you'll lift the curse.

779
00:46:31,054 --> 00:46:34,842
Look, Fred, I, I, I'm sorry about this family curse and all,

780
00:46:34,878 --> 00:46:36,755
but, I've really gotta be getting back.

781
00:46:36,789 --> 00:46:41,168
I, I, I've got Japanese executives coming over to discuss a possible merger.

782
00:46:41,203 --> 00:46:42,698
I am announcing my engagement.

783
00:46:42,767 --> 00:46:45,235
I am giving my father-in-law a cappuccino machine.

784
00:46:45,235 --> 00:46:47,459
You can't exactly leave.

785
00:46:47,494 --> 00:46:49,893
What do you mean, "Can't exactly leave"?

786
00:46:49,927 --> 00:46:54,411
The curse is on anyone who stays in the house past midnight.

787
00:46:54,445 --> 00:46:58,477
I can't even believe I am having this conversation.

788
00:46:58,512 --> 00:47:00,250
Well, why do you think Susan can't leave?

789
00:47:00,284 --> 00:47:05,185
She stayed over one night with Dennis, that was six months ago.

790
00:47:05,221 --> 00:47:07,445
Now come on, it's worth a try.

791
00:47:07,479 --> 00:47:10,121
For Celia's sake.

792
00:47:10,156 --> 00:47:11,754
And what's she got to do with it?

793
00:47:11,790 --> 00:47:13,041
She likes you.

794
00:47:13,075 --> 00:47:14,292
She does?

795
00:47:16,065 --> 00:47:17,281
What am I saying?

796
00:47:17,316 --> 00:47:19,540
This is ridiculous. I don't even believe in curses.

797
00:47:19,574 --> 00:47:21,938
You're still here, aren't you?

798
00:47:27,743 --> 00:47:29,446
When's dinner, Mom. I'm starved.

799
00:47:29,480 --> 00:47:33,025
As soon as Uncle Henrick and Aunt Bonnie arrive.

800
00:47:33,061 --> 00:47:35,772
(MUMBLES)

801
00:47:35,806 --> 00:47:37,892
He's not a Nazi.

802
00:47:37,962 --> 00:47:41,611
I, er, think I'm gonna try to use that phone again.

